     8	---
     9	
    10	## 1. Why this document exists
    11	
    12	KBM Hoag and Pivot Interiors are merging. Both companies completed independent NetSuite/Orion BRD discovery with GSI in 2025. Both started — but have not finished — configuration work. With the merger now in motion under Matt Hoag's leadership, decisions about how the *merged* company will operate inside Orion need to be made before configuration resumes in June.
    13	
    14	This document proposes the approach, structure, and methodology for the deliverable that will drive those decisions: a **Process Unification Recommendation** covering all 10 BRD process areas. Once approved, the full recommendation will be drafted, reviewed by both leadership teams, and used as the working agenda for an on-site decision session.
    15	
    16	This document is **not** the recommendation itself. It is a proposal for how the recommendation will be built and delivered. **Section 4 contains a fully worked CRM pilot** so reviewers can react to the actual format rather than abstract structure.
    17	
    18	## 2. What the merger needs from the system, in plain language
    19	
    20	Two companies that competed against each other in California — KBM as the Knoll dealer, Pivot as the Herman Miller dealer — are now one MillerKnoll dealer under MillerKnoll's encouragement. They run differently:
    21	
    22	- **KBM** is smaller, less systemized, and outsources operational complexity (delivery, install). The benefit is agility; the cost is tribal knowledge that doesn't scale.
    23	- **Pivot** is larger, more sophisticated, and runs operations in-house (delivery, install, warehousing, field service). The benefit is process maturity; the cost is overhead that smaller activities don't always justify.
    24	
    25	Each company built its BRD reflecting its own DNA. The merged company can't run both. Matt has to decide, process area by process area, which company's playbook the merged organization adopts — or whether a hybrid is the right answer.
    26	
    27	## 3. Reconciliation principle
    28	
    29	The recommendation document applies the same principle to every process area. Stating it up front matters because it's the lens through which every recommendation in the document was made — and the lens through which Matt and the leadership teams should evaluate disagreement.
    30	
    31	> **Default to the simpler operating model. Layer in sophistication only where it protects margin, compliance, scale, or a capability one company brings that the other does not.**
    32	
    33	In practice this resolves to three cases:
    34	
    35	| Case | Default |
    36	|------|---------|
    37	| **Both companies do the activity** (e.g., quoting, order entry, finance close) | Lean toward the simpler model. KBM's agility is a feature, not a deficiency, where the activity doesn't require Pivot's controls. |
    38	| **Only one company does the activity** (e.g., in-house operations — Pivot only; certain commission arrangements — Pivot only; project management with Workfront — Pivot only) | That company's processes lead. The other company's staff onboard into them. |
    39	| **Merged scale exceeds either legacy company's prior scale** | More sophistication may be appropriate than either had alone. The recommendation will say so explicitly when it applies. |
    40	
    41	Note the deliberate framing of "agility" vs. "red tape." Pivot's processes carry overhead partly *because Pivot does more activities*. KBM's agility is partly *because KBM outsourced complexity*. The recommendation will treat both companies' strengths charitably.
    42	
    43	## 4. The ALIGN / ADAPT / ACCOMMODATE asymmetry
    44	
    45	GSI's discovery framework classifies each requirement as:
    46	- **ALIGN** — out-of-the-box Orion capability, no decision
    47	- **ADAPT** — client changes process to fit Orion, minor decision
    48	- **ACCOMMODATE** — Orion is customized for the client, real cost/scope decision
    49	
    50	For unification, the meaningful asymmetries are when a requirement is classified differently across the two BRDs:
    51	
    52	| KBM | Pivot | What it means |
    53	|-----|-------|---------------|
    54	| ALIGN | ALIGN | No decision. Standard Orion. |
    55	| ALIGN | ACCOMMODATE | Pivot is paying for sophistication KBM doesn't need. Decide: keep the customization or drop it? |
    56	| ACCOMMODATE | ALIGN | KBM wants something Pivot didn't ask for. Same question, reversed. |
    57	| ADAPT | ADAPT | Both companies adapt — but possibly *to different target processes*. Decide which target to align on. |
    58	| ACCOMMODATE | ACCOMMODATE | Both customize. Are they leaning the same direction? If yes, keep. If diverging, decide. |
    59	
    60	This asymmetry is the actual decision space for Matt. Where both are ALIGN there's nothing to discuss; where they diverge, the document's job is to make the trade-off legible.
    61	
    62	## 5. Document structure (the deliverable)
    63	
    64	The full Process Unification Recommendation will follow this structure:
    65	
    66	```
    67	1. Executive Summary               (1–2 pages, Matt-readable in 10 minutes)
    68	2. Strategic Foundation
    69	   2.1 Reconciliation principle
    70	   2.2 Account & licensing posture (NetSuite, partner of record)
    71	   2.3 Cultural & change-management posture
    72	3. At-a-Glance Index               (the traffic light — see §6)
