    14	## 4.02.1 What both companies do today
    15	
    16	**KBM** runs a relationship-driven CRM out of Zendesk, with deal-level data tracked inconsistently because CRM use has been optional. When a deal closes, customer information is re-entered manually into Core for order processing, and RFPs are managed in Asana on a separate timeline that marketing only sees once a formal request is submitted. The team has internalized the cost of this fragmentation — the team's own description of the data quality is "poo in, poo out" — and has come into Orion implementation explicitly looking to make CRM use mandatory and unified. KBM's pain point is *consistency*. The discipline they want from Orion is not optional.
    17	
    18	**Pivot** runs a structured CRM out of HubSpot for opportunity management, with downstream quoting and invoicing already in NetSuite (and migrating from D365). Forecasting is exported monthly from HubSpot to Excel, weighted manually, and pivoted for executive review — accurate but lagging by days or weeks. RFPs are tracked separately in Monday.com. Pivot's organization is structured around four divisions (Enterprise, Venture, Public, Construction Solutions) with a hierarchy of executive → SVP/GM → sales operations → designers/reps. Pivot's pain point is *real-time visibility and integration*; their data discipline is already good, but the round trip through Excel costs them speed and the disconnect between CRM and downstream systems costs them margin visibility.
    19	
    20	Both companies are migrating away from fragmented CRM stacks. Both want unified opportunity-to-quote-to-order-to-invoice flow inside Orion. Both want mobile entry, role-based dashboards, and segmented reporting. The shape of "what a good CRM looks like" is broadly aligned. The disagreements are in the details — and the details matter.
    21	
    22	## 4.02.2 Where they converge (no decisions required)
    23	
    24	The following requirements are common to both BRDs and classified as ALIGN on at least one side, ADAPT on the other (a process change with no customization):
    25	
    26	- Unified Opportunity → Quote → Sales Order → Project flow inside Orion
    27	- Mobile quick-add / quick-entry for leads and opportunities
    28	- Activity tracking (calls, emails, meetings) with email integration (Outlook SuperSync on Pivot side; equivalent on KBM)
    29	- Document attachment to opportunity records
    30	- Role-based dashboards (rep, manager, executive)
    31	- Drill-down from any dashboard metric to underlying records
    32	- Segmented contact lists / list builder for marketing
    33	- Multi-role contacts (one person can have multiple roles)
    34	- Customer Portal for self-service quote / invoice visibility
    35	- Win/loss reason code capture
    36	- Migration of legacy CRM data with deduplication
    37	
    38	These are tagged ALIGN in the merged BRD and require no decision. Configuration proceeds against standard Orion capability.
    39	
    40	## 4.02.3 Where they diverge — and what's at stake
    41	
    42	Eleven divergences. Each is presented as: what KBM does, what Pivot does, classification asymmetry, what it means for the merged company, recommendation, and the decision Matt owns.
    43	
    44	### D-1. Pipeline stage model and forecasting
    45	
    46	| | KBM | Pivot |
    47	|---|---|---|
    48	| Stages | 7 stages (Lead/Prospect, Qualification, Needs Analysis, Proposal/RFP, Negotiation, Closed Won, Closed Lost) | 4 stages (Analysis 25%, Qualified 50%, Quote 80%, Closing 95%, Win/Loss) |
    49	| Forecast filter | 70%+ probability threshold for "forecast" inclusion | All weighted, no threshold; commit/best-case/pipeline derived from probability |
    50	| Probability change rights | Configured by stage | Per-role permission to override percentages |
    51	| Classification | ADAPT | ALIGN |
    52	
    53	**What it means.** Pivot's 4-stage model is cleaner and matches Orion's native opportunity stage structure with less customization. KBM's 70% threshold is a useful filter for executive forecast discipline, but it can be *implemented as a forecast view*, not a separate stage system — so KBM doesn't lose what they wanted.
    54	
    55	**Recommendation.** Adopt Pivot's 4-stage pipeline as the merged-company default (Analysis 25%, Qualified 50%, Quote 80%, Closing 95%, Win/Loss). Layer in the KBM 70%+ threshold as a separate **Commit Forecast** view alongside the standard weighted-pipeline view. Allow per-role percentage override at the SVP / Sales Manager level (Pivot's requirement) since it doesn't conflict with KBM.
    56	
    57	**Decision for Matt.** Confirm: 4-stage pipeline + Commit Forecast view at 70%+ threshold? *Default: yes.*
