./_Unification/Doc A - Account & Renewal Memo.md:27:KBM's 5-year prepayment is a financial asset that does not transfer if the account is abandoned. Walking away from it to consolidate inside Pivot's account would mean writing off the prepaid value and continuing to pay annual fees indefinitely — the worst possible combination. Continuing inside KBM and letting Pivot's contract lapse at renewal preserves the asset and removes a recurring cost.
./_Unification/Doc A - Account & Renewal Memo.md:29:NetSuite leadership confirmed this same posture in our recent meeting: their preferred path is for the merged company to operate inside the prepaid KBM account. NetSuite will not consolidate the two accounts (they would lose revenue), but they are not opposed to one of them lapsing — and Pivot's annual structure makes the lapse mechanically simple.
./_Unification/Doc A - Account & Renewal Memo.md:33:1. **Do not renew the Pivot Interiors NetSuite contract.** Allow it to lapse at the May 2026 renewal date. No counter-offer, no extension.
./_Unification/Doc A - Account & Renewal Memo.md:34:2. **Initiate Partner-of-Record transition** for the KBM account so that the merged company's GSI/Proprio relationship is correctly recorded against the surviving account. License-related decisions should wait until the POR transition completes.
./_Unification/Doc A - Account & Renewal Memo.md:36:4. **Communicate the decision** to Sandra Rudloff and Pivot leadership before the renewal lapse so the lapse is intentional, not surprise. The unification messaging is "we are operating inside KBM's account because the contract structure made that the right financial choice; the system will reflect both companies' best processes."
./_Unification/Doc A - Account & Renewal Memo.md:40:Per recent reconciliation, Pivot has approximately 200 employees in their NetSuite account today, against approximately 100 purchased licenses. Of those, only 10–15 employees actively use NetSuite; the rest are inactive employee records. **Do not request additional licenses until the Partner-of-Record transition is complete.** The merged company's true license requirement should be sized after consolidation against the KBM contract, and any expansion should be negotiated with NetSuite at that point — not pre-emptively against either legacy footprint.
./_Unification/Doc A - Account & Renewal Memo.md:45:- **Operational timing of the Pivot system shutdown** — Pivot's account will remain accessible through the lapse and through whatever data extraction window is required for migration. Specific cutover dates are scheduled inside the Realize phase plan.
./_Unification/Doc A - Account & Renewal Memo.md:52:| Pivot users lose access before migration window closes | Schedule data extraction *before* the renewal lapse; if extraction takes longer than expected, negotiate a short paid extension on Pivot account only as a contingency |
./_Unification/Doc A - Account & Renewal Memo.md:53:| NetSuite changes posture during POR transition | POR transition initiated in writing; reference NS leadership's verbal alignment on consolidation path |
./_Unification/Doc A - Account & Renewal Memo.md:55:| License sizing miscalculation post-merge | License count is held flat through POR transition; resized only after merged organization is operating |
